1. Introduction 
1.1 Overview 
This project implements a complete Big Data processing pipeline using Apache Spark and 
MongoDB to ingest, process, analyse, and store large-scale Twitter data about US airline 
sentiment. The goal is to demonstrate real-world Big Data engineering skills using industry
standard tools. 
1.2 Dataset 
The Twitter US Airline Sentiment dataset was selected for this project. It contains public 
tweets directed at major US airlines collected in February 2015, pre-labelled with sentiment 
categories. 
Detail 
Information 
Dataset Name 
Twitter US Airline Sentiment 
Source 
Kaggle 
Total Records 
14,478 tweets 
Airlines Covered 
United, US Airways, American, Southwest, Delta, Virgin 
America 
Time Period 
February 2015 
Sentiment Labels 
Positive, Neutral, Negative 
1.3 Problem Statement 
Airlines receive thousands of customer complaints and compliments on social media daily. 
Processing and analysing this data at scale can reveal critical insights about service quality, 
customer pain points, and airline performance. Traditional tools cannot handle this volume 
efficiently, making Big Data technologies essential. 
1.4 Project Objectives 
• Ingest and clean raw tweet data using Apache Spark 
• Store processed data in MongoDB with an optimized schema 
• Perform large-scale analysis using Spark SQL and PySpark 
• Compare query performance between Spark SQL and MongoDB Aggregation 
• Generate meaningful visualizations and insights 
2. Methodology 
2.1 Tools & Technologies 
Tool Version Purpose 
Apache Spark (PySpark) 4.1.1 Large-scale data processing 
MongoDB 7.0 NoSQL data storage 
Python 3.x Programming language 
Pandas Latest Data manipulation 
Matplotlib & Seaborn Latest Data visualization 
Java JDK 17.0 Spark runtime environment 
Jupyter Notebook Latest Development environment 
 
2.2 Pipeline Architecture 
The pipeline follows a structured 5-step approach: 
• Step 1 — Data Ingestion: Load raw CSV into Spark, clean and preprocess 
• Step 2 — Spark Processing: Apply transformations, groupBy, word frequency analysis 
• Step 3 — MongoDB Storage: Insert clean data with optimized indexes 
• Step 4 — Spark SQL: Run complex SQL queries and performance benchmarks 
• Step 5 — Visualization: Generate charts and extract key business insights 
 
2.3 MongoDB Schema Design 
The data is stored in a single collection with the following structure: 
Field Type Description 
tweet_id String Unique identifier for each tweet 
airline_sentiment String Sentiment label: positive / neutral / negative 
Field Type Description 
airline_sentiment_confidence Float Confidence score (0.0 to 1.0) 
negativereason String Reason for negative sentiment (if applicable) 
airline String Airline name 
retweet_count Integer Number of retweets 
text String Original tweet text 
clean_text String Cleaned tweet text (processed) 
tweet_created String Tweet creation timestamp 
tweet_location String User location (if available) 
 
2.4 MongoDB Indexing Strategy 
Six indexes were created to optimize query performance: 
Index Type Purpose 
airline Single field Fast filtering by airline name 
airline_sentiment Single field Fast sentiment-based queries 
negativereason Single field Fast negative reason lookups 
tweet_id Single field Unique tweet identification 
airline + airline_sentiment Compound Optimized airline+sentiment queries 
 
  
3. Implementation 
3.1 Data Ingestion & Cleaning (Notebook 01) 
• Loaded raw Tweets.csv using spark.read.csv () with inferSchema 
• Selected 9 relevant columns from original 15 
• Removed rows with null values in key columns (tweet_id, airline, text) 
• Removed duplicate tweet_ids to ensure data integrity 
• Cleaned tweet text: removed @mentions, URLs, and special characters 
• Final clean dataset: 14,478 records successfully stored in MongoDB 
3.2 Spark Processing (Notebook 02) 
• Computed overall sentiment distribution across all tweets 
• Broke down sentiment by individual airline 
• Calculated average sentiment confidence scores per airline 
• Identified top 10 negative complaint reasons 
• Performed word frequency analysis on negative tweets (with stopword removal) 
• Identified most retweeted tweets per airline 
3.3 MongoDB Queries (Notebook 03) 
• Used aggregation pipeline to compute sentiment counts 
• Grouped by airline and sentiment for detailed breakdown 
• Identified top 10 negative reasons using $match and $group 
• Measured query execution time with index vs without index 
• Identified best and worst performing airlines 
3.4 Spark SQL Queries (Notebook 04) 
• Registered cleaned DataFrame as a temporary SQL view 
• Computed sentiment distribution with percentage using window functions 
• Generated airline scorecard showing positive/neutral/negative counts 
• Analysed top negative reason per airline 
• Measured hourly tweet activity patterns 
• Compared Spark SQL vs MongoDB aggregation performance (3-run average) 
3.5 Performance Note 
Parquet format was tested for bonus points but could not be implemented due to a known 
Windows + Hadoop native library limitation in the local development environment. In a 
Linux or cloud environment (AWS EMR, Google Dataproc), Parquet would provide 3-5x faster 
read speeds and 60-70% storage reduction compared to CSV format. 
