4.5 Key Visualizations 
The following charts were generated and saved to the report folder: 
• Chart 1: Pie chart showing overall sentiment distribution (63% negative, 21% neutral, 
16% positive) 
• Chart 2: Grouped bar chart comparing sentiment across all 6 airlines 
• Chart 3: Horizontal bar chart showing top 10 negative complaint reasons 
• Chart 4: Heatmap showing average sentiment confidence score per airline 
• Chart 5: Bar chart comparing Spark SQL vs MongoDB query execution time 
 
  
5. Conclusions 
5.1 Lessons Learned 
• Apache Spark is highly effective for large-scale data cleaning and transformation 
• MongoDB indexing significantly improves query performance for simple lookups 
• Spark SQL provides more flexibility for complex multi-column analytical queries 
• Windows environment has limitations with Hadoop native libraries (Parquet support) 
• Compound indexes in MongoDB optimize frequently combined query patterns 
• Data cleaning is critical — raw tweet text contains noise that affects analysis quality 
5.2 Key Business Insights 
• United Airlines has the most negative customer feedback and needs urgent service 
improvements 
• Customer service is the number one complaint across all airlines (2,883 tweets) 
• Southwest Airlines has the best positive-to-negative ratio among major carriers 
• Flight delays and cancellations are the second biggest pain point after customer 
service 
• Virgin America, despite fewer tweets, has the healthiest sentiment distribution 
5.3 Potential Improvements 
• Implement real-time tweet streaming using Spark Streaming or Kafka 
• Build a machine learning sentiment classifier using Spark MLlib 
• Deploy on cloud infrastructure (AWS EMR or Google Dataproc) for full Hadoop 
support 
• Implement Parquet and Avro format comparison on a Linux environment 
• Build an interactive dashboard using Streamlit or Gradio 
• Extend analysis to include more recent airline tweet data 
